==== The Triad of Irrational Proportions

Three substitution rules, three irrational proportions. $sqrt(2)$ from the mirror and its stable companion, $phi.alt$ from the Fibonacci swinging substitution, $rho$ from the Padovan morphism. They have emerged one at a time through the preceding sections, each responding to a specific structural question, each imposing its own consistency condition on the swing. What remains to be seen is whether they form a coherent family, or whether their coexistence is simply the accidental outcome of three independent exercises. The present section argues for the former: that the three irrational proportions are not three numbers that happen to appear in three different rules, but three positions in a single structured triad, each occupying an optimum under constraints that the other two cannot satisfy simultaneously. The full formal development of this claim — the catalogue of admissible rules, the Pisot condition that regulates stability, the perceptual viability constraints that bound the tempo range — is given in @sec:synthesis of Book IV. The present section presents the same conclusion in its musical form.

The common principle from which all three rules emerge has been visible from the start. A substitution rule on an alphabet of durations produces, under iteration, a hierarchy of nested rhythmic patterns. For this hierarchy to carry a coherent swing at every level — for the rhythm to be audible as a swung subdivision at the beat, at the half-beat, at the quarter-beat, and so on indefinitely — the ratio between long and short durations must be preserved by the rule itself. This is the _consistency condition_ that each rule satisfies: a condition not on what the rule does at the first application, but on what the rule must do to iterate without distorting the swing it carries. The three irrational proportions are the positive irrational solutions to three such conditions, one for each rule.

What distinguishes the three cases is not the principle but the _constraints_. A binary rule with inequality has several admissible forms, each optimising a different property. The mirror rule $S arrow.r L, L arrow.r S S$ optimises _compactness_: its inflation at each iteration is the smallest possible, $sqrt(2)$ itself, meaning that the rule produces the shortest word at each step among all rules sharing its ratio. But it pays for this compactness with a loss of dynamical stability — the letters cluster under iteration, the swing character evaporates from one level to the next, and the ratio $sqrt(2)$ is preserved only in the asymptotic counting, not in the local structure. Musically, this is the rule of the _paired subdivision_: the mirror pair of Section 3.2.2, which in practice is stabilised by external references — the clave, the bell, the ensemble — and is rarely pushed beyond one or two levels of recursion.

The Fibonacci swinging substitution $S arrow.r L, L arrow.r L S$ optimises a different property: _interleaving_. It is the minimal binary rule whose iterates maintain maximal entropy — the tightest distribution of letters compatible with aperiodicity. Its ratio $phi.alt$ satisfies the consistency condition while the letters interleave in the pattern characteristic of Sturmian words, and its inflation equals its ratio, giving the rule a strict self-similarity that the mirror lacks. Where the mirror drifts under iteration, Fibonacci self-corrects: the golden ratio is a _dynamical attractor_ of the substitution, and small perturbations decay back toward it. The cost of this stability is a larger inflation — longer words at each iteration, therefore fewer levels of recursion fitting within the same tempo range — but the reward is a rhythmic structure that can be sustained by a single performer without external reference. Musically, this is the rule of _solo recursion_, of the swing that holds together by its own consistency.

A second binary rule, $S arrow.r S L, L arrow.r S S L$, returns the ratio $sqrt(2)$ in a stable form. Unlike the mirror, this rule satisfies the same dynamical stability condition as Fibonacci, and its inflation $1 + sqrt(2)$ sits between the mirror's $sqrt(2)$ and the ternary values to be encountered next. The existence of this second rule reveals something structurally significant: the ratio $sqrt(2)$ admits _two_ substitution realisations, one unstable and compact, one stable and dense. No other binary ratio has this double nature. It is as if $sqrt(2)$ — the meantone of the rhythmic continuum, the balanced 50% swing of Section 3.2.3 — occupied a privileged position in the substitutional landscape, expressible under both the constraint of compactness (mirror) and the constraint of stability (second rule), at the cost of no other binary rule sharing either property with it.

